The progress that Alphafold has made over the last few years is truly breathtaking, but I feel like we aren't seeing the forrest through the trees.  As exciting as it is to think about all of the diseases we are going to be able to cure in the short term, it doesn't seem like anyone is discussing the long term impacts on population.  By circumventing the spread of disease on such a large scale, we are messing with a system that has seen life propagate successfully on earth for roughly 3.7 billion years.  I feel like the short term gains are going to pale in comparison to the suffering and hardships caused over time. On average, 50 million people die from disease each year worldwide.  Many of those in developing nations.  Let's say we are able to eradicate half of those deaths, not to mention the potential to increase average life expectancies and fertility rates.   It's not hard to see the potential for massive societal collapse due to an explosive population surge.
